feedback.answer: The panelist gave concise details on what was done both incorrectly and correctly during the round. It was a fair delivery of feedback, and I believe that it was spoken in a very gracious way.
Ms. Jade was able to point out the strengths and weaknesses of our case even though it was very general. More power to you, Ma'am!!
Judged the round on an unfair metric - little to no credit on our contributions; only focused on our shortcomings.
Every argument was pointed out for both teams.

The panel sounded like they were building the case of the opposite side, ignoring the blatant responses carried on opp from opposition whip. Despite the analysis, a vague justification was given, and was not enough to convince us as to why gov took the win over opp. Had they given us a more in-depth analysis, maybe we would have understood their decision.
The feedback was well-delivered and organized. It made me see what both sides did correctly and the ways that we could improve on in making our arguments.
Though at some parts it was quite unclear, she was still able to convince us as to why she made that decision.

Although we were initially confused as to why we lost during the round, her explanation was very clear and gave us insight on the practical perspectives we missed. We thank her for her good adjudicating.
She was good adjudicator even if she was the lone judge in our round. She was able to give comprehensive feedback on both sides that will be at benefit for our future rounds. More power to you Miss!

We appreciate and took note of his comments and our lack of errors. However, we believe that during his speech he was too fixed on trying to correct our claims through the lens of the opposition. Though we would not claim that he may be biased, we would only like to voice out that it would've given us more insights if he gave an analysis as a person outside the debate and not already championing one house just because of morality.
The chair was fair and honest in terms of giving justification.
The chair was fair enough in giving comments and justification.

The judge weighed some crucial materials in the round, but stepped in by giving material that was not heard in the debate. The judge's standards were acceptable, but it was not enough for us to believe that their decision stood since it seemed like they were only explaining what the winning team's contributions were, without explaining to us how our contributions were lacking. There were also some materials that were not weighed in, because it seemed they were biased to the winning team especially when they credit new material from the reply speech.
The panelist was able to give fair and reasonable comments.
It was quite unclear at some point but generally, he was also convincing and unbiased.

The adjudicator delivered the remarks in a relatively slow way. However, the adjudicator pointed out the cases in a structured manner. It was good that the loopholes and the mistakes of both sides were pointed out clearly.
The panelist was able to give justification properly, however there are some parts that are unclear to us.
The win was poorly explained, with only 1-2 sentences of justification per standard. Furthermore, crucial material was not taken into account and was not mentioned during the oral adjudication.

1. The adjudicator applied standards like responses, mechanisms, depth of analysis, etc. but there was no follow through on how one team won over the other using those standards. The materials that were brought up can be applied to the standards but the judge didn't. 2. There were little to no comparatives on where individuals who are member of the aging population are better handled and where can countries who have aging populations advance their interests. We believe that this were the core issues in the round that were not discussed.
Adj can definitely improve the structure of their OA so it can be followed better. Otherwise, it was a clear and well-substantiated OA.
She failed to see our points and did not convince us enough for us to side with her decision.

Although there was good analysis on what occured during the round itself and what points of value were analyzed, I believe it could have been further evaluated, especially on the side of the government which won this debate since she failed to mention certain key aspects that the chairperson did.

Inconsistent adjudication, also sounded like panel was building up the case of gov. OA was hinged on summarizing the debate, instead of weighing contributions and informing us on what both sides lacked, and what made one side win over the other. Did not mention specific standards for their decisions, and only told us what went on during the debate.
The chair was able to give justification honestly and fairly.
The discussion was well explained and easy to understand, explained the lacking aspects in the world building and extensions, as well as what both sides failed to do.

The adjudicator's evaluation demonstrates a firm command of the material because their comprehension is amply demonstrated in their analysis. However, despite their insightful analysis, there are still some particular areas that need improvement and further research to raise the OA's general quality.
Great adjudicaing, clearly pointing out the core issues of the round and the reasons as to why we lost.
Analyzed the arguments pragmatically and mentioned all the aspects both sides missed. He also put the burdens and merits of both sides and explained the clashes well and who won for each point.

Although I agree with his decision, I believe that he could have given further analysis to our side in order for us to better our claims. He also did not highlight the very important points our side raised.

We strongly disagree with the decision made by the adjudicator, as we believe they overlooked crucial burdens and framings presented by the Government side during the debate. The omission of these important aspects significantly influenced the outcome, and it seemed as though the adjudicator was building up the case for opposition, constructing arguments to support their decision. We firmly assert that considering the overlooked framings would have contributed significantly to a fairer and more accurate judgment. Their issues directly overlook the intrinsic value of medical professionals to save lives, if this wasn't the case then the patients would have died at the get go then. We think that the adj concedes to many arguments that Opp presented even if there were lacking mechanisms to prove it in contrast to the oral adjudication of the chair where he presented fair credited contributions from both houses and recognizing where both houses fell short while amounting to a fair judgement.

I think while there was reasonable level of discussion as to what occurred during the round, I think there was somewhat a lack of discussion as to why we were scored lower in the round. Unlike the chairperson, I think there was an analytical gap in her adjudication.

The background of the adjudicator was quite noisy, and so it was relatively hard to focus. However, the points or comments presented were clear and concise and in line with the comments of the other adjudicators on the panel.
The panelist was able to give the justification and comments in the round, however some parts were unclear to us.
Discussed what happened in the round well but didn't really explain or expound on some aspects with clashes during the round, only tackling a few.

The adjudicator's assessment reveals a clear grasp of the subject matter, as their understanding is clearly reflected in their analysis. Nevertheless, despite their insightful examination, there remain specific areas that require further improvement and exploration to elevate the overall quality of the OA.

Discussed the lacking mechanizations and the missed points of both sides, as well as the disconnect within the arguments due to lack of world-building and lack of a working model from the government bench.
The adjudicator has provided feedback with commendable analysis and a comprehensive grasp of the debate's nature. Nevertheless, I perceive that some areas need further improvement.

I am a big fan of the way he was able to adjudicate our debate. He was able to point out the strengths of our side, as well as of the government side. He was also able to give a critical analysis of our debate. More power to you sir!!
Very excellent and intricate analysis that missed nothing. Weighed well the benefits and harms of both sides and provided insight on as to how we can be better as debaters.
I very much appreciate his critical analysis of both sides. He was able to give feedback that we could very much use in the upcoming rounds.
Out of the three adjudicators, I think his was the most accurate and in-depth. It discussed the several levels of argumentation of the round and it was very constructive.
The chair was able to give justifiable comments.
wasn't able to consider our counterarguments (e.g., "provided no alternatives"); gave personal opinion on the matter
The mentioned chair is very precise with their adjudication.

Gave a more nuanced justification and explained contributions, and properly weighed why one contribution won over the other. Also helped us understand the decision more, all the while explaining what the round lacked, and how each response was accounted for.
It was such a great adjudication, structure was unique and the points were explained.
I love his style of of adjudicating!! Very specific and very direct to the point. He was also able to give points to that we can use to improve our arguments for the upcoming rounds.

The adjudicator was very gracious and chill in providing the comments of the round. Critical yet reasonable comments were given to both the opposition and government. The weighing between pros and cons were fair and justifiable.
The chair was fair enough to give justification.
He was also convincing enough that we agree with his decision.
This adjudicator ignored the whip of the government side where there were answers to some of her questions which favored the government side.
I am glad she recognized the key points of both sides. I am also glad that she offered advice for us in the upcoming months.

The adjudicator became very assumptive when summarizing the case for both houses. The oral adjudicator missed a lot of points including the framework on how transparency exists on side Govt on where families and patients are going to be aware of the treatment, but the treatment will still forego, this has been understood well by the chair in his OA while it's clear that the case has been misrepresented to the panelists. The weighing was not convincing enough to make us understand that opposition's bulk wins over the well mechanized analysis coming gov. The adjudicators says that both teams needed to engage on the worst and best case, we think that if that was the case then Govt should have taken the round because we've engaged on the co-optability of Opp's best and worst case and proved how it is better.
Ultimately the adjudication wasn't as substantial because they never clearly give an explicit comparative as to how the decision came to be.
There is a need to explicitly compare the materials that were brought in the round. There was an attempt to bring back the arguments of both GOV and OPP but the justification is unclear.
She had an organized speech which made it clear to us why she chose that decision.

While the adjudicator mentioned some core points in the argument, I don't think they substatiated well why we lost considering they also failed to acknowledge what the government side failed to rebut on our arguments. We agree that there were lacking aspects in our argumentation and failed to defend some points on our side, we just weren't satisfied with her explanation compared to the other adjudicators.

The judge poorly explained their standards, and they judged the debate on the one liners of the winning team without telling us where we lacked. We felt that there were a lot of contributions that they ignored when judging, and only seemed to listen to the winning team. There were no clear standards as to how they judged the round, since they only judge on the one liners of the winning team, despite their standards being 1) argumentation, and 2) depth of analysis. We did not understand how one liners could be credited as depth of analysis.
The chair was able to give reasonable and fair comments. However, there are cases that were unclear to us.

tournament.motion: THR the rise of digital content creators
THO the villain editFor the purposes of this debate, a "villain edit" refers to the phenomenon in reality TV wherein an individual is framed by the show as antagonistic or unlikeable

THO the rise of intertextuality in media critiqueFor the purposes of this debate, "intertextuality" refers to a way of describing or understanding pieces of media as being derivative of other media (e.g. "Tick, Tick... Boom! is the Avengers for theater kids", "Avatar: The Last Airbender is the Citizen Kane of our times", "Elden Ring is the Breath of the Wild of Souls games")

THR the expansion of aquaculture in developing countriesAquaculture, also known as fish farming, involves raising aquatic organisms in controlled environments. It meets the global demand for seafood, enhances food security, and supports economic development. However, its expansion can harm marine ecosystems by causing habitat loss and increasing the vulnerability of coastal communities to disasters.

THBT environmental activists must boycott and actively denounce the COP27Every year, world leaders gather to discuss climate change at COP, which stands for Conference of the Parties. Since 1995, the United Nations has brought together the 197 signatories to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCC) to work on how to tackle climate change.

THS the use of insurrection as a legitimate strategy for environmental activism in Asian countriesInsurrection refers to a violent uprising or rebellion against authority, often aiming to overthrow the government or disrupt societal order.
THS optimizing the educational curricula of college majors with professional licensure exams towards passing those exams (e.g. removing general education subjects perceived as unnecessary)

THW abolish the autonomous and deregulated statuses for HEIsThe Commission on Higher Education (CHED) grants "autonomous" and "deregulated" statuses to certain Higher Education Institutions (HEIs). These statuses have benefits that include freedom from regular monitoring from CHED, priority in granting of subsidies, freedom to offer new programs and put up branches or satellite campuses without having to secure permits, and privilege in determining their curricular programs. Deregulated HEIs must still secure permits for new programs and campuses.
THBT universities should only offer programs/courses with high likelihoods of employment opportunities after graduation
THW discontinue all forms of research that aim to cure persons with disabilities (e.g. autism, hearing impairments, visual impairments, physical disabilities)
In cases of life-threatening medical situations, THW give doctors full autonomy to decide the patient's treatment and care
In countries with aging populations, THW heavily subsidize research into reversing the aging process in humans
As a young and up-and-coming talent in Philippine show business, THW choose a career in the indie film industry
THBT it is justified for the cultural artifacts of a country to remain in possession of a foreign entity when its country of origin is currently incapable of taking care of it

TH, as the anti-AI art movement, would aggressively generate AI art to oversaturate the datasetsAI art generators work by using machine learning algorithms to create new artwork. This is when a large dataset of existing paintings, drawings, and other art are used to help the program differentiate between different art styles and techniques. Recently, programs have begun referencing existing AI art to generate new AI art which has yielded worse results.

THP a world where it's allowed to donate or transfer ligtas pointsFor the purposes of this debate, everyone receives "ligtas points" for good deeds done and lose ligtas points for bad deeds. These determine whether or not you receive salvation for the afterlife.
THS the use of religious institutions' radical and leftist interpretations (e.g. liberation theology) of their doctrine to areas suffused with wide inequalities and extreme poverty
THS the medicalization of religious traumaThe medicalization of religious trauma refers to the process of viewing religious trauma as an illness that requires treatment.

TH, as the couple, would not search for their biological childYour husband took a paternity test with your 10-year-old child. After showing him the negative results, he accused you of cheating. You told him to take the tests together and as it turns out, they are not your child either. You learned that your child had been swapped at the hospital 10 years ago.

THP a world where children are adopted through closed adoptionsA closed adoption is one where no identifying information about the birth family or the adoptive family is shared between the two, and there is no contact between the families. An open adoption allows for some association among the birth parents, adoptive parents, and the child they adopted.

THW permanently delete the criminal history of children in conflict with the law, after they have served their sentence"Children in conflict with the law" or CICLs refers to individuals who are below the age of majority (typically 18 years old) and have been involved in criminal activities or are accused of committing offenses that are considered illegal under the legal framework of a particular jurisdiction.
THS popularizing the idea that having a child at this point in time is an act of violence

TH, as progressive feminists in this motion, would cut ties with Andrea"Andrea" is a prominent female feminist in a conservative developing nation. Her work has helped push for more policies that uphold gender equality and reduce gender discrimination, and many feminists in that nation look up to her. Unfortunately it has recently come to light that Andrea does not consider trans women to be women and believes they have no place in the feminist movement.

TH, as a woman offered a glass cliff position, would choose to acceptThe glass cliff (not to be confused with glass ceiling) refers to women ascending to corporate leadership positions during challenging circumstances where the risk of failure is high.
